'''马文·李·明斯基'''（{{lang-en|Marvin Lee Minsky}}，{{bd|1927年|8月9日|2016年|1月24日|catIdx=Minsky, Marvin}}），生於美国紐約州[[紐約市|紐約市]]，美国科學家，專長於[[認知科學|認知科學]]與[[人工智能|人工智能]]领域，[[麻省理工学院|麻省理工学院]]人工智能实验室的创始人之一，著有几部人工智能和哲学方面的作品。1969年，因為在人工智能領域的貢獻，獲得[[圖靈獎|圖靈獎]]。

== 生平 ==
生於[[猶太人|猶太人]]家庭中，高中就讀[[菲利普斯学院|菲利普斯学院]]。高中畢業後，在1944年至1945年間，服役于[[美国海军|美国海军]]，參與[[第二次世界大戰|第二次世界大戰]]。1950年于[[哈佛大学|哈佛大学]]获得数学学士学位，1954年于[[普林斯顿大学|普林斯顿大学]]获得数学博士学位。自1958年起在麻省理工学院任教，擔任东芝媒体艺术与科学教授（Toshiba Professor of Media Arts and Sciences）、麻省理工学院[[电子工程|电子工程]]与[[计算机科学|计算机科学]]教授，直到他過世為止。

他有數項發明，如1957年發表的[[共聚焦顯微鏡|共聚焦顯微鏡]]，1963年發表的[[頭戴式顯示器|頭戴式顯示器]]。他與[[西摩爾·派普特|西摩爾·派普特]]共同發展了第一個以[[Logo語言|Logo語言]]建構的機器人，命名為海龜（Turtle）。1951年，他設計並建構了第一部能自我學習的[[人工神经网络|人工神经网络]]機器，SNARC。1952年，他發明會自行關閉電源的[[無用機器|無用機器]](Useless Machine)<ref name=Pesta>{{cite news|last=Pesta|first=Abigail|title=Looking for Something Useful to Do With Your Time? Don't Try This|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887323628804578348572687608806.html?KEYWORDS=useless+machine|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=12 March 2013|page=1}}</ref>

1956年，他與约翰·麦卡锡組織了[[達特茅斯會議|達特茅斯會議]]，在這場會議中，人工智慧的概念被提出，在之後形成了一個新的學門。在麻省理工學院，他與[[约翰·麦卡锡|约翰·麦卡锡]]共同創立了人工智慧研究室（[[MIT計算機科學與人工智慧實驗室|MIT計算機科學與人工智慧實驗室]]的前身）。

閔斯基奠定了[[人工神经网络|人工神经网络]]的研究基礎。

2016年1月24日，閔斯基因腦內出血病逝，享壽88歲<ref>[http://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/201601270008-1.aspx 擁有怪獸大腦 人工智慧先驅明斯基辭世]，中央社，2016年1月26日</ref>。

==榮譽==
明斯基曾获得多项荣誉。他是[[美国工程院|美国工程院]]和[[美国科学院|美国科学院]]院士，于1969年获得[[图灵奖|图灵奖]]，1990年获得[[日本國際獎|日本國際獎]]，1991年获得{{en-link|IJCAI卓越研究奖|IJCAI Award for Research Excellence}}，2001年获得[[富蘭克林獎章|富蘭克林獎章]]（Benjamin Franklin Medal）。

<!--

Minsky's [[patent|patent]]s include the first head-mounted graphical display (1963) as well as the confocal scanning microscope (a predecessor to today's widely used [[confocal_laser_scanning_microscope|confocal laser scanning microscope]]) and, jointly with [[Seymour_Papert|Seymour Papert]], the first [[Logo_programming_language|Logo]] "turtle". Minsky also built, in [[1951|1951]], the first randomly wired neural network learning machine, [[SNARC|SNARC]].

<blockquote>[Edit]: I did patent my 1956 confocal microscope, but the patent expired before anyone built a second one. We did not bother to patent the display or the turtle, assuming that they were perfectly obvious. Looks like 'obviousity' is no longer relevant to patenting. -- Marvin Minsky</blockquote>

He wrote the book ''Perceptrons'' (with Seymour A. Papert), which became the foundational work in the analysis of artificial neural networks. Its criticism of unrigorous research in the field has been claimed as being responsible for the virtual disappearance of artificial neural networks from academic research in the 1970s. 

<blockquote>[Edit]: So it was claimed--but actually our mathematical analysis was to show why bigger perceptrons didn't get better at solving hard problems.  And contrary to a popular rumor, almost all our theorems still apply to multilayer
feedforward neural networks.  But curiously, no one seems to have proved this, and Papert and I went on to other subjects . -- Marvin Minsky
</blockquote>

Minsky was an adviser on the movie [[2001:_A_Space_Odyssey_(film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]] and is referred to in the movie and book,

:"Probably no one would ever know this; it did not matter. In the 1980s, Minsky and Good had shown how neural networks could be generated automatically—self replicated—in accordance with any arbitrary learning program. Artificial brains could be grown by a process strikingly analogous to the development of a human brain. In any given case, the precise details would never be known, and even if they were, they would be millions of times too complex for human understanding."

Minsky was almost killed due to an accident on the set.

Minsky was also responsible for suggesting the underlying plot of [[Jurassic_Park|Jurassic Park]] to [[Michael_Crichton|Michael Crichton]] during a walk on the beach in [[Malibu,_California|Malibu]]. At that point in the meanderings which led to the classic novel and film, the dinosaurs were conceived as [[automata|automata]]. Crichton later drew on his biomedical training to conceive the dinosaurs as arising through cloning.

<blockquote>[Edit]: It wasn't about automata.  My idea was that even if the DNA in the fossils was gone, it might have affected the positions of the atoms that replaced it.  The result would be very noisy, but a dinosaur might have had a trillion cells, so if we had the locations of all the atoms in the fossil, we might be able to reconstruct the DNA by statistical analysis. Unlikely though, and Crichton got the better idea about insects in amber.  I'm sure it was in Malibu indeed, because [[Farrah_Fawcett|Farrah Fawcett]] came running by while we were talking. -- Marvin Minsky
</blockquote>

Minsky is an actor in an artificial intelligence [[koan|koan]] (attributed to his student, [[Danny_Hillis|Danny Hillis]]) from the [[Jargon_file|Jargon file]]:

:In the days when [[Gerald_Jay_Sussman|Sussman]] was a novice, Minsky once came to him as he sat hacking at the [[PDP-6|PDP-6]]. 
:"What are you doing?", asked Minsky. 
:"I am training a randomly wired [[neural_net|neural net]] to play [[Tic-tac-toe|Tic-tac-toe]]" Sussman replied. 
:"Why is the net wired randomly?", asked Minsky. 
:"I do not want it to have any preconceptions of how to play", Sussman said. 
:Minsky then shut his eyes. 
:"Why do you close your eyes?", Sussman asked his teacher. 
:"So that the room will be empty." 
:At that moment, Sussman was enlightened.

<blockquote>
[Edit]: What I actually said was, "If you wire it randomly, it will still have preconceptions of how to play. But you just won't know what those preconceptions are."  -- Marvin Minsky
</blockquote>

==Trivia==
Minsky is a childhood friend of the [[Yale_University|Yale University]] critic [[Harold_Bloom|Harold Bloom]], who has referred to him as "the sinister Marvin Minsky."

==Selected works==
*''Neural Nets and the Brain Model Problem'', Ph.D. dissertation, Princeton University, 1954. The first publication of theories and theorems about learning in neural networks, secondary reinforcement, circulating dynamic storage and synaptic modifications. 
*''Computation: Finite and Infinite Machines'', Prentice-Hall, 1967. A standard text in computer science. Out of print now, but soon to reappear. 
*''Semantic Information Processing'', MIT Press, 1968. This collection had a strong influence on modern computational linguistics. 
*''Perceptrons'', with [[Seymour_Papert|Seymour Papert]], MIT Press, 1969 (Enlarged edition, 1988). 
*''Artificial Intelligence'', with Seymour Papert, Univ. of Oregon Press, 1972. [[Out-of-print_book|Out of print]].
* [http://web.media.mit.edu/~minsky/papers/AlienIntelligence.html Communication with Alien Intelligence], 1985
*''Robotics'', Doubleday, 1986. Edited collection of essays about robotics, with Introduction and Postscript by Minsky. 
*''[[The_Society_of_Mind|The Society of Mind]]'', Simon and Schuster, 1987. The first comprehensive description of the Society of Mind theory of intellectual structure and development. See also ''The Society of Mind (CD-ROM version)'', Voyager, 1996.
*''The Turing Option'', with [[Harry_Harrison|Harry Harrison]], Warner Books, New York, 1992. Science fiction thriller about the construction of a superintelligent robot in the year [[2023|2023]].
* ''The Emotion Machine'' [http://www.simonsays.com/content/book.cfm?sid=33&pid=510225], Simon and Schuster, due September 2006. ISBN 978-0-7432-7663-4

